Airbnb Pricing and Rating in Seattle in 2016¶

- Business understanding¶

Seattle Airbnb open data is a sneak peek into the Airbnb activity in Seattle. There are three datasets:

  1. listing: the dataset records 3818 airbnb home information in Seattle scraped from Airbnb on the specific date Jan 4, 2016.
  2. calendar: the dataset records water bill of the 3818 airbnbs for a whole year since the latest scraped date.
  3. reviews: reviews for the airbnbs until the latest scraped date.

I'd like to answer three questions from the above datasets:

  1. How many property types of airbnb and their price were in Seattle?
  2. When to visit Seattle is most economy for family tourism living in airbnb?
  3. Q3: Are reviews helpful for choosing airbnb?

Assessment conclusion:¶

  • The data set of Calendar records 3818 airbnbs price information for 2016 entile year.
  • There isn't price information when a bnb is not available.
  • The need of data wrangling
    • data type: the data type of data to be date
    • binary data: map t for True and f for False
    • price: delet currency symbol and change data type to float.
  • Vacancy value could be driven to a new set, then merge to listing.

In [9]:
# change the data types
calendar["date"] = pd.to_datetime(calendar["date"])
calendar["available"] = calendar["available"].map({"t": True,
                                                   "f": False})
calendar["price"] = calendar["price"].str.replace(",","").str.replace("$","").astype(float)

# del datum when bnbs are not available
#calendar = calendar[calendar["available"]].drop("available",axis=1)

# sadd a column named month,elect data in 2016
calendar = calendar[calendar["date"] <= dt.datetime(2016,12,31)]
calendar["month"] = calendar["date"].apply(lambda x: x.month).astype(str)

Assessment conclusion:¶

  • 3818 airbnb with 92 features
  • 11 features which are unique value gives information that the dataset is about all available airbnb in Seattle with no requirement of license from Jan 4,2016. These data can be deleted.
  • 6 features with missing values exceeding 50% could be deleted.
  • 8 features are about url. However, thumbnail_url, medium_url suggest whether the bnb are linked to social medium while others provide less predictive information.
  • data type id and host_id should be better to be string.
  • name and host_name with no predictive information should be delete

2.2 Initial Data Clean¶

  • drop 11 unique value features
  • drop 6 features with missing values exceeding 40%
  • create a feature named linked_to_media while dropping 8 url features
  • del name and host_name
In [16]:
# unique features
listing_col = listing.columns.values
listing.drop(listing_col[unique_col_ind], axis=1, inplace=True)

# missing values
listing_col = listing.columns.values
missingValue_col_ind = np.argwhere(listing.isnull().mean() > 0.4).flatten()
listing.drop(listing_col[missingValue_col_ind],axis=1, inplace=True)

# urls
listing_col = listing.columns.values
listing["linked_to_media"] = listing["thumbnail_url"].notnull()
url_col_ind = np.argwhere([("url" in i) for i in listing.columns]).flatten()
listing.drop(listing_col[url_col_ind], axis=1, inplace=True)

# del name and host_name
listing.drop(["name","host_name"],axis=1,inplace=True)

Assessment conclusion

  • summary,space,neighborhood_overview, notes and transit are descriptive sentences. They are decomposed into more specific features thereafter. So they may be deleted.
  • features from host_id to host_identity_verified are about host characteristics:
    • host_response_rate and host_acceptance_rate should be numerate. And host_acceptance_rate has only 2 values 100% and 0%. 99% value of host_acceptance_rate is 100%. So it's like a unique variable that could be delete.
    • 99% value of host_has_profile_pic is t. So it's like a unique variable that could be delete.
    • host_verifications and host_identity_verified are expressing same thing about host verification that one is ways and another is results. host_identity_verified is more meaningful and host_verifications should be deleted.
    • host_since could be changed to host_owned_years that we can know how long the host owned until Jan 4,2016.
    • host_location is about where the host live. It's better to seperate the location into at seattle or not, then it might suggest whether the host lives beyond Seattle would accept lower rents as inconvenient to do the business.
    • host_neighbourhood provides less useful information, so it could be deleted.
    • host_about is host self-describe. It could be deleted.
    • host_is_superhost should be change data type to binary
  • features from steet to is_location_exacat are about location:
    • locations provide similar information,and only neighbourhood_group_cleansed should be kept.
    • latitude and longitud could be kept if I have geography tools.
    • "is_location_exact" maybe say location is different between GPS information and address.
  • features from property_type to extra_people are about accommodation characteristics.
    • amenities are basic services. I don't want keep it.
    • price information should be numerate.
  • features from calendar_updated to last_review are about review records date information.They could all be deleted.
  • features from instant_bookable to requir_guest_phone_verification are about condition.
    • data type of instant_bookable should be bool
    • 99% values between require_guest_profile_picture and require_guest_phone_verification are same. Only one feature should be remain that is require_guest_profile_picture.

2.4 2nd Data Clean¶

descriptive:

  • del summary,space,neighborhood_overview, notes and transit

host characteristics:

  • del host_about,host_neighbourhood,host_acceptance_rate,host_verifications,host_has_profile_pic
  • change date types of host_response_rate and host_acceptance_rate to numerate
  • change host_since to host_owned_years
  • change host_location to host_live_in_seattle
  • change date types of host_is_superhost to binary
In [25]:
# del host_about,host_neighbourhood,host_acceptance_rate,host_verifications,host_has_profile_pic
listing = listing.drop(["host_about","host_neighbourhood","host_acceptance_rate","host_verifications","host_has_profile_pic"],axis=1)

# change date types of host_response_rate and host_acceptance_rate to numerate
listing["host_response_rate"] = listing["host_response_rate"].str.split("%").str[0].astype(float)/100

# change host_since to host_owned_years
listing["host_since"]=[round((dt.datetime(2016,1,4) - pd.to_datetime(listing["host_since"][i])).days/365.25,2) for i in range(listing.shape[0])]
listing = listing.rename(columns={"host_since":"host_owned_years"})

# change host_location to host_live_in_seattle
listing["host_location"] = listing["host_location"].apply(lambda x: np.nan if str(x) == "nan" else "seattle" in x.lower())
listing = listing.rename(columns={"host_location": "host_live_in_seattle"})

# change date types of host_is_superhost to binary
listing["host_is_superhost"] = listing["host_is_superhost"].map({"f": False,
                                                                 "t": True})
listing["host_is_superhost"] = listing["host_is_superhost"].astype(bool)

location:

  • del street,neighbourhood,neighbourhood_cleansed,city,state,zipcode,smart_location,latitude and longitud
  • change the data type of is_location_exact to bool

Assessment conclusion:

There are 6 parts in the numerate data similar to non-numerate features. They are:

1. host
2. location
3. accommodation 
4. price
5. rent condition
6. reviews

For the host part, it records host_owned_years,host_response_rate,host_listings_count,and host_listings_count(it deplicated to host_listings_total_count should be deleted). There is no relation among them.

Location is GPS position which conveys similar information to neighbourhood_group_cleansed. So I don't like to using these features.

Data of accomodation suggests airbnbs are all small business with high kurtosis and positive skewness. They are all positive correlated. More accommodats, more bedrooms, beds and bathrooms. That's reasonable.

Prices are positive correlated. However, total cost customer paid should include cleaning_fee into the price.

In condition parts:

- minimum_nights: 99% airbnbs require minimum nights less than 1 week. 
- minimum_nights: most datum locate 7,14,30,60,90,365 and 1125. They are 1 week, 2 weeks, 1 month, 2 monthes, 1 season, 1 year and 3 years. 
- avaiability means how many days available in 30/60/90/365 days. They are highly correlated. However only 30 days is meaningful, because most values of difference between availability of 30 and 60 are concentrated at 30 and 0.

In review parts:

  • review socre is conposed by 6 parts. They are accuracy, cleanliness, checkin, communication, location and value.
  • frequency of review is irrelative to review socores whereas it could be infer whether the bnb is hot.

3.2 Data Clean¶

  • date to be datetime

Question 1: How many property types of airbnb and their price were in Seattle?¶

1. Prepare Data¶

1.1 Data Gathering¶

1.2 Handle categorical and missing data¶

- Handle categorical data

In [45]:
for col in q1.select_dtypes(include=["O"]).columns:
    try:
        if q1[col].dropna().unique().shape[0] <= 2:
            q1 = pd.concat([q1.drop(col,axis=1),
                            pd.get_dummies(q1[col], prefix=col, prefix_sep="_",drop_first=True, dummy_na=False)],axis=1)
        else:
            q1 = pd.concat([q1.drop(col,axis=1),
                            pd.get_dummies(q1[col], prefix=col, prefix_sep="_",drop_first=False, dummy_na=False)],axis=1)
    except:
        continue

Conclusion:¶

I set models of random forest and linear regression to observe what features are more important to price and what features' correlation to price. Unfortunately, the scores of the models are not good enough and unstable. However, the results are stable. They show roughly the relationship between price and features. Thereful, I'd to dig the relationship more directly.

when the airbnb is not available, there is no price provided. There are 2 possible. One is out of service while the other is full booking.

Reviews score for airbnb is combined by 6 independent parts. They were accuracy, cleanliness, checkin, communication, location and value. Value is the most important feature and the location is the least.
